appointment of Lara over, say, his own chief-of-staff, <b>James Uthmeier</b=
>, who could be a placeholder for DeSantis until he needs a new job in 2026=
=2E<br/><br/>In any case, the Grenell s=
nub is only the latest in a series of=20=
Trump choices that are sure to be controversial with one or another constit=
uency. Some Republican allies have privately expressed concerns after Trump=
 plucked two members of Congress, <b>Elise</b> <b>Stefanik</b> and <b>Mike =
Waltz</b>, to serve as
ambassador to the United Nations and national security advisor, respectivel=
y, placing additional pressure on whatever slim majority Speaker <b>Mike Jo=
hnson </b>will have to work with come January. Other MAGA members of the Ho=
use didn=E2=80=99t bother pitching their services, believing that there was=
 no way to get into the administration because of that margin, and are now =
irked to see their colleagues get the nod. There are also gripes that =E2=
=80=9Cestablishment=E2=80=9D staffers with r=C3=A9sum=C3=A9s connected to <=
b>Elaine Chao</b> and <b>Bill Barr</b>, two ex-secretaries non grata, are i=
nvolved in the transition, rather than MAGA soldiers from the campaign. It=
=E2=80=99s all of a piece with the broader resentment bubbling to the surfa=
ce as the president-elect elevates old political hands with Washington cred=
 over fringier grassroots characters who have been waiting in the wings. <b=
r/><br/>As for Democrats, they=E2=80=99re bracing themselves for a particul=
arly bruising photo-op tomorrow, when <b>Joe Biden</b>
does the classy thing and invites Trump to the White House to discuss the t=
ransition=E2=80=94an official act that Trump refused to perform in 2020. Of=
 course, the Democrats are already throwing stones at Biden, but this diffi=
cult day for him will be the only picture anyone is looking at.<br/><br/><i=
>But first, here=E2=80=99s Abby Livingston with the latest vote-counting be=
fore Thune-Cornyn-Scott decision day=E2=80=A6</i><br/></p>
