          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Despite the thunder=
 from MAGA world, Senate Republican insiders I=E2=80=99ve spoken with in re=
cent days tell me that the pressure campaign to install Florida Sen. <b>Ric=
k Scott</b> as majority leader tomorrow=E2=80=94bypassing =E2=80=9Cthe John=
s=E2=80=9D and nuking <b>Mitch McConnell</b>=E2=80=99s managed succession=
=E2=80=94is about as welcome in the upper chamber as local birdwatchers try=
ing to force their marshland agenda on a country club. The expectation head=
ing into tomorrow morning=E2=80=99s election is that Scott will place third=
 in the first round of voting, setting up a one-on-one battle between <b>Jo=
hn Thune</b> of South Dakota and <b>John</b> <b>Cornyn </b>of Texas later i=
n the morning. Here is the readout on election eve: <br/><br/><ul style=3D"=
margin:0;color:#000000;font-size:16px;line-height:30px;margin-top:0;margin-=
bottom:0;list-style-type:square;mso-special-format:bullet"><li><i>The leade=
rboard</i>: At first blush, it appears Scott has momentum, per multiple rep=
orts. Wisconsin=E2=80=99s <b>Ron Johnson</b>, Tennessee=E2=80=99s <b>Bill H=
agerty</b>, Kentucky=E2=80=99s <b>Rand Paul</b>, and fellow Floridian <b>Ma=
rco Rubio </b>all support him. For now, only Missouri=E2=80=99s <b>Josh Haw=
ley</b> publicly supports Cornyn. Meanwhile, Thune is backed by Oklahoma=E2=
=80=99s <b>Markwayne Mullin</b>, Montana=E2=80=99s <b>Steve Daines</b>, Nor=
th Dakota=E2=80=99s <b>Kevin Cramer</b> and <b>John Hoeven</b>, and fellow =
South Dakotan <b>Mike Rounds</b>.<br/><br/>But I=E2=80=99m hearing that man=
y more G.O.P. senators are quietly inclined to align with either Thune or C=
ornyn. Since McConnell announced earlier this year that he was stepping dow=
n from leadership, Thune has been perceived as the frontrunner within the B=
eltway. He=E2=80=99s a dragon slayer in his own right, coming
to Washington in 2005 after ousting <i>another</i> Senate majority leader, =
Democrat <b>Tom Daschle</b>, from office. And yet, given the lack of public=
 commitments for Thune, it=E2=80=99s quite possible that Cornyn will become=
 the first Senate leader from Texas since <b>L.B.J.</b>=E2=80=94a remarkabl=
e interval when you consider the amount of money Texas donors deploy to Rep=
ublican senators across the map. <br/><br/></li><li><i>One extraordinary st=
at</i>: Incredibly, this is the first time in nearly <i>30 years</i> that t=
he Senate G.O.P. conference has held a competitive leader race, dating back=
 to <b>Trent Lott</b>=E2=80=99s successful run in 1996. The only sitting Re=
publican senators who were around for <i>that</i> vote are McConnell and<b>=
 Chuck Grassley</b>. For everyone else, this is new terrain. In the last tw=
o Senate leader elections, Mitch McConnell and <b>Bill Frist</b> had their =
races sewn up before voting even started. <br/><br/>Leadership races are th=
e most emotional and frequently
<i>personal</i> contests on the Hill, as evidenced by the raucous, bitter f=
ight to replace <b>Kevin McCarthy</b> last year. That=E2=80=99s especially =
true of the McConnell succession battle, wherein the dividing lines reinfor=
ce the notion that this is a popularity contest more than an ideological ba=
ttle. Since this is a secret-ballot election, a senator=E2=80=99s vote is u=
nlikely to ever become public, despite the MAGA pressure campaign for trans=
parency. Indeed, even the members running in these leadership races are oft=
en unsure how their colleagues voted. I=E2=80=99ve personally witnessed <i>=
victorious</i> members complain that a vote count was off, meaning their co=
lleagues hadn=E2=80=99t been honest with them about their support. </li></u=
l></td>
         </tr>
