          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><i>News, notes, and=
 analysis aplenty about some local media institutions, #Resistance media, a=
nd Trump=E2=80=99s impact on the industry (edited for length and clarity)=
=E2=80=A6</i><br/><br/><b><i>Dylan Byers</i>: I cover legacy media, which i=
s obviously going through a lot of pangs. Given the fragmented environment,=
 what should the business model and overall strategy be if you=E2=80=99re, =
say, <i>The Washington Post</i>?</b><br/><br/><i>Jim VandeHei: </i>It pains=
 me to say <i>The Post</i> is a hot mess. It looks like they=E2=80=99re in =
a big financial hole. That=E2=80=99s probably solvable. But the bigger prob=
lem is the constant tension between management and reporters, and I think b=
oth sides have to take some damn ownership of it. <b>Will</b> <b>Lewis</b> =
has obviously done a lot of things that have angered his staff, and that=E2=
=80=99s completely on him. But I would also say to any
reporter, <i>You have to understand how hard this business is right now</i>=
=2E We don=E2=80=99t have time to spend da=
ys, weeks, and <i>months</i> in rev=
olt, not doing our jobs and not figuring out how we can provide distinct co=
ntent to distinctive audiences. If you=E2=80=99re doing that, you=E2=80=99r=
e just not going to have a business. <br/><br/>Meanwhile, <i>The New York T=
imes</i> has a national footprint and a strong sense of self, and they=E2=
=80=99re happy to be the dominant publication of the left, and to figure ou=
t ways to monetize that while picking up people who don=E2=80=99t necessari=
ly consider themselves liberal but care about the topics they cover. I don=
=E2=80=99t know what room that gives <i>The Post</i>. They can say, <i>Well=
, we=E2=80=99re going to own Washington</i>. Good luck! It=E2=80=99s a very=
 crowded and competitive space. It=E2=80=99s just really hard to find repor=
ters who are routinely telling you things about subjects that people care a=
bout, and that are basically essential to some group of people.
That=E2=80=99s the challenge. <br/><br/><b>So what do you do about that? </=
b><br/><br/>Dude, <b>Bezos</b> is richer and smarter than I=E2=80=99ll ever=
 be; I assume Will is a very bright guy. If there was an easy solution, the=
y would=E2=80=99ve done it. You have to somehow figure out what part of the=
 news ecosystem <i>The Washington Post</i> can dominate <i>decisively</i>=
=E2=80=94not just be a participant in it, not just provide decent coverage =
that wins awards. It has to offer distinctive content that somebody <i>has<=
/i> to have, and therefore they=E2=80=99ll pay for it and engage with it on=
 a regular basis. They have to make it so that anyone who=E2=80=99s in Wash=
ington <i>has</i> to read it. And by the way, that doesn=E2=80=99t just app=
ly to <i>The Post</i>=E2=80=A6 most companies get in trouble if they don=E2=
=80=99t have a clear sense of self, and if that clear sense of self can=E2=
=80=99t make money. <br/><br/><b>How has your own business changed over the=
 last year, and does the incoming Trump administration change the plan in a=
ny
way?</b><br/><br/>We realize we=E2=80=99ve got to be able to pick the audie=
nces where we have a right to win, and if we win, we can monetize it. We=E2=
=80=99ve really organized the company around that. We went through a painfu=
l set of layoffs in the summer, and a lot of that was designed to tighten o=
ur focus. We have to put all of our investment into being able to own our v=
ery specific audiences. And so, from a national perspective, we=E2=80=99re =
all-in on technology, business, media, politics, and policy. That=E2=80=99s=
 the bread and butter. That=E2=80=99s one chunk of the company; the other c=
hunk is local. We=E2=80=99re in 30 cities, and we=E2=80=99re going to annou=
nce soon that we=E2=80=99ll be in more cities. Local is one of our growth b=
usinesses. We just came off a pretty good year in which we doubled local-fo=
r-local advertising. <br/><br/><b>What=E2=80=99s your =E2=80=9Cright to win=
=E2=80=9D in local?</b><br/><br/>It=E2=80=99s kind of the idea of the smart=
 friend in your pocket=E2=80=94this idea that I have a daily newsletter wri=
tten by two or
three or four people who have expertise in the city that I live in, and the=
y=E2=80=99re helping me navigate it. That means what=E2=80=99s happening in=
 the news and what=E2=80=99s happening in politics, but it also means, what=
 are the cool places to go see? What=E2=80=99s hot in the city that I live =
in? <br/><br/>That=E2=80=99s a big reason Cox bought us; they love local. W=
e=E2=80=99re going to continue to be very bullish in local over the long te=
rm, but we=E2=80=99re going to stay very focused and not try to be everythi=
ng to everybody. We=E2=80=99re not going to compete in spaces where we don=
=E2=80=99t think we can win. And that means you have to make really, really=
 hard decisions=E2=80=A6 <br/><br/><b>Mike</b> [<b>Allen</b>] and I have wr=
itten columns now eight consecutive days. We=E2=80=99re still working as ha=
rd, if not harder, than we did 30 years ago, because it=E2=80=99s a war. An=
d the people who win are the people who grind it out.<br/><br/><i>Listen to=
 the full conversation on Dylan=E2=80=99s excellent new podcast, <u><a href=
